OARMEN XVIII.

It was usual to offer sacrifice to Faunus at the beginning of spring, though the Fau- nalia did not take place till the Nones of December. (See C. i. 4. 6 and 17.) This ode is very elegant, especially the picture of rustic security and cheerfulness in the last two stanzas. The confusion of the Greek Pan with the Latin god Faunus has been noticed

before and is well known. ARGUMEN T.
